    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Cousinia aspera improperly are that it can cause diarrhea, develop diarrhea, and trigger diarrhea due to its saponin content which can irritate the digestive system and alter gut bacteria, inducing vomiting in severe cases. This is because saponins can also cause an imbalance in gut flora leading to gastrointestinal disturbances. Furthermore, Cousinia aspera has been known to trigger allergic reactions in some individuals, particularly those with sensitive skin or respiratory systems. The improper use of Cousinia aspera can also lead to other health issues such as nausea and stomach discomfort. This is because the plant's toxic compounds can cause an overstimulation of the nervous system and an imbalance in electrolytes.",
    "uses": "Cousinia aspera is a plant species known to have medicinal properties, particularly in traditional medicine. Its leaves and roots are used to treat various health conditions. In folk medicine, it is used to treat fever, inflammation, and digestive issues. The plant's extracts have been studied for their potential antiseptic and antimicrobial properties. Further research is needed to fully understand the plant's medicinal uses and potential health benefits.",
    "taxonomy": "Cousinia aspera is classified within the family Asteraceae, which is a large and diverse group of flowering plants commonly known as daisies or sunflowers. The genus Cousinia itself is part of the subfamily Carduoideae, which comprises thistle-like plants. Cousinia aspera is native to the mountainous regions of Central Asia, specifically in the Himalayas and parts of China. The species is further classified as a type of annual or biennial plant, growing from 30-100 cm in height. Its exact classification may also include the tribe Cardueae, a group of thistle-like plants within the Asteraceae family.",
    "benefits": "Cousinia aspera has been traditionally used in medicine for its potential health benefits, including anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. It is believed to possess antibacterial and antifungal properties, which can aid in the treatment of various infections. The plant may also help to reduce oxidative stress and protect against cell damage. Additionally, Cousinia aspera is thought to have hepatoprotective properties, which can help to safeguard the liver from damage. More research is needed to fully understand the extent of Cousinia aspera's health benefits.",
    "parts": "Cousinia aspera is a species of flowering plant. The medicinal parts of Cousinia aspera are not well-documented, but it is used in traditional medicine in certain regions. Its roots and leaves may be used in herbal remedies, but more research is needed to confirm their effectiveness. The plant's medicinal properties may include anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects. Further studies are required to fully understand the potential medicinal uses of Cousinia aspera.",
    "intro": "Cousinia aspera, also known as Cousinia, is a plant species belonging to the Asteraceae family, native to the mountainous regions of Central Asia. It has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, providing relief from various health issues such as fever, inflammation, and respiratory problems, thanks to its analgesic, anti-inflammatory, and expectorant properties. The bioactive constituents of Cousinia aspera include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which are responsible for its medicinal effects. The most common herbal preparations made with Cousinia aspera include decoctions, infusions, and tinctures, which are used to treat a range of health conditions, including colds, coughs, and sore throats."
